{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-905271a3775c0e0a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t Verifier-Guided Twelve-Tone Composition:A Generate–Verify–Repair Harness for Symbolic Music Generation Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more &times; Back to arXiv License: CC BY 4.0 arXiv:2607.11334v1 [cs.AI] 13 Jul 2026 Verifier-Guided Twelve-Tone Composition: A Generate–Verify–Repair Harness for Symbolic Music Generation Congren Dai 1 , 2 , Danni Zhao 1 , Enyang Liu 1 , Michael Ching Yam 1 , Zhancheng Guo 1 , 2 , Siyi Gu 1 , Wentao Yang 1 , Bo Dai 1 , Xiaobing Li 1 , and Maosong Sun 1 , 2 🖂 🖂 🖂 Corresponding author. Abstract Large language models can produce superficially legal twelve-tone scores that collapse into degenerate textures. We introduce a neuro-symbolic harness that wraps a language-model proposer in a generate–verify–repair–trace loop with symbolic verification. The complete pipeline improves event-local consistency without claiming whole-piece legality. Across 40 40 controlled tasks and four paired models, audited delivery yield rises from 13.3 % 13.3\\% under raw generation to 48.1 % 48.1\\% with the harness, which explicitly abstains otherwise. The pass rate of a narrower collision and serialisation-consistency check rises from 33.5 % 33.5\\% to 58.3 % 58.3\\% , while degeneracy remains near 0.05 0.05 , including under exploratory adversarial prompting. A blinded evaluation by five experts also shows a descriptive aggregate preference for harness candidates over raw generation in adherence, perceived legality, coherence, and overall quality. 1 Introduction Twelve-tone (serial) music, a compositional method in which an ordered tone row of pitch classes governs harmony and melody through transposition, inversion, and retrograde (Schoenberg 1950 ; Straus 2016 ) , is an attractive testbed for controllable generation: its core rules are crisp and formal, yet musically interesting serial realisations often depend on global organisation (Perle 1991 ) . More generally, maintaining long-range coherence is a central challenge in symbolic music generation (Huang et al. 2019 ) . This combination exposes a failure mode that is easy to miss when “rule legality” is the only metric. A model instructed to prioritise legality can satisfy the letter of the rules with a degenerate score (a few sustained chords, collapsed voices, near-empty bars) that is nominally compliant but musically empty. This behaviour is analogous to specification gaming : it satisfies the stated rule-based proxy while defeating the intended musical objective. Reward-hacking work studies the related, but not identical, case in which optimisation exploits a misspecified objective or reward proxy (Amodei et al. 2016 ; Pan et al. 2022 ; Skalse et al. 2022 ) ; here we elicit shortcuts through adversarial prompts rather than training-time reward optimisation. We argue that a structural intervention is more reliable than prompting alone. A deterministic verifier records hard-rule violations, and a row-aware repair operator projects proposed material back onto the active row slice whenever possible. The large language model (LLM) is retained where it is genuinely useful (high-level planning and note-level proposals that drive musical quality), while symbolic components control pitch-class assignment and surface unresolved violations explicitly. Unlike prompt-only self-correction, the symbolic layer evaluates executable events rather than model-generated claims. Its trace records which row positions survive repair, making dropped or modified material inspectable in the delivered artefact. This setting is a clean microcosm of a broader challenge in neuro-symbolic generation: automatic proxies can be satisfied without producing useful outputs, and process-level checks need to be distinguished from independent checks on the delivered artefact. Twelve-tone music sharpens the tension because legality is a crisp Boolean property, whereas musical quality is global and is precisely what a legality-maximiser sacrifices. Practically, the harness returns either an audit-verified score or an explicit failure with an inspectable record of retained, repaired, and dropped material. Methodologically, separating process diagnostics from delivered-artefact audits offers a useful pattern for other structured generators, such as code or plans, even though their domain predicates would need to be redesigned. The target rule set is also unusually hard to enforce by decoding: it includes cross-voice and long-range properties (each voice must track a scheduled twelve-tone stream, and no two simultaneously sounding voices may share a pitch class), so it cannot be checked from a single token prefix. To study it we run six language models across 40 40 controlled tasks with length and texture sweeps, adversarial (red-team) briefs, module ablations, a corpus-distance analysis against 20 20 human serial works, and a blind pairwise study with five experts. Figure 1: Overview of the harness: an LLM proposer generates candidate events (Stage 1), and a deterministic verifier with a row-aware repair ladder checks or modifies them while recording a per-note trace (Stage 2). A final delivered-score audit gates release (Section 3.5 ). Concretely, we (1) formalise serial composition as constrained sequence generation over ℤ 12 \\mathbb{Z}_{12} : an order- 48 48 transformation group, a core event-consistency target defined by hard constraint predicates, and separate process diagnostics and final-audit decisions (Section 3 ); (2) introduce a generate–verify–repair–trace harness with a row-preserving repair operator and a generator/verifier lockstep invariant, yielding event-local row projection and monotone best-attempt selection rather than unconditional whole-piece legality (Section 3.4 ); and (3) evaluate, over the fixed task bank, robustness to degeneracy-inducing prompts, length and texture scaling, model capability, cost, and expert preference. 2 Related Work Symbolic music generation. Prior systems address long-range structure (Huang et al. 2019 ) , controlled infilling (Thickstun et al. 2024 ) , text-to-music attributes (Lu et al. 2023 ) , and multi-track adversarial generation (Dong et al. 2018 ; Muhamed et al. 2021 ) . They are not organised around a post-hoc verifier that reports domain-level rule violations. SerialGen instead generates twelve-tone rows algorithmically (Feitosa et al. 2022 ) , without an LLM proposer or verify–repair loop. Constrained and grammar-constrained decoding. Prefix-constrained methods reject invalid next tokens using incremental parsers or completion engines (Scholak et al. 2021 ; Poesia et al. 2022 ; Geng et al. 2023 ) . Other approaches use inference-time energies (Qin et al. 2022 ) , training-time logical losses (Ahmed et al. 2023 ) , or constraint programming followed by LM ranking (Bonlarron and Régin 2024 ) . Our cross-voice, complete-row constraints instead use an external stateful verifier paired with repair. Verifier-guided generation and self-correction. Related approaches include process reward models (Lightman et al. 2024 ) , generative verifiers (Zhang et al. 2025 ) , self-refinement (Madaan et al. 2023 ) , and feedback-based reflection (Shinn et al. 2023 ) . Unlike these model-mediated approaches, our harness pairs deterministic symbolic checking with explicit repair; Soft rules remain a one-shot, no-verifier baseline. Reward hacking and specification gaming. Optimising an imperfect reward proxy can reduce performance under the true objective (Amodei et al. 2016 ; Skalse et al. 2022 ; Gao et al. 2023 ) . Examples include capability-threshold failures (Pan et al. 2022 ) and reward-model over-optimisation (Gao et al. 2023 ) ; narrower rewards are not generally unhackable (Skalse et al. 2022 ) . We test analogous prompted shortcuts using delivered-score metrics rather than process diagnostics alone. 3 Problem Formulation and Methodology 3.1 Design Rationale Twelve-tone music as a target. Twelve-tone composition suits generate–verify–repair because its serial operations and aggregate structure are precisely defined (Perle 1991 ; Babbitt 1960 ) . We operationalise them as predicates over timed events, adding explicit row-form tags, aggregate completion, and cross-voice non-collision checks (Section 3.3 ). A per-voice row cursor lets repair project a candidate onto its tagged row slice; the LLM handles planning, voicing, and rhythm, while the symbolic layer checks hard rules and records per-note traces. Event representation. Internally, a composition is a multiset of timed events with MIDI-integer pitches (Section 3.3 ). The compact schema exposes pitch class m mod 12 m\\bmod 12 , onset, duration, voice, row tag, and register directly to the predicates and repair operators, avoiding notation-format parsing. Notation and rendering. Composition, verification, and repair use only the canonical event record. Our renderer deterministically exports the same retained events to LilyPond and MusicXML. All blind-evaluation conditions share this implementation path, while corpus-distance analysis uses the same monophonic pitch-line reduction (Appendix A ). 3.2 Pitch Classes and the Row-Form Group Let ℤ 12 = { 0 , 1 , … , 11 } \\mathbb{Z}_{12}=\\{0,1,\\dots,11\\} be the set of pitch classes under octave equivalence (Straus 2016 ) . A prime row (tone row) is an ordered aggregate P = ( P 0 , … , P 11 ) P=(P_{0},\\dots,P_{11}) , i.e. a bijection { 0 , … , 11 } → ℤ 12 \\{0,\\dots,11\\}\\to\\mathbb{Z}_{12} ; every pitch class occurs exactly once (Schoenberg 1950 ; Perle 1991 ) . Three canonical operators act on rows: transposition T n ​ ( x ) = ( x + n ) mod 12 , \\displaystyle T_{n}(x)=(x+n)\\bmod 12, (1) inversion I ​ ( x ) = ( − x ) mod 12 , \\displaystyle I(x)=(-x)\\bmod 12, (2) retrograde R ​ ( x 0 , … , x 11 ) = ( x 11 , … , x 0 ) . \\displaystyle R(x_{0},\\dots,x_{11})=(x_{11},\\dots,x_{0}). (3) T n T_{n} and I I act pointwise on a row; R R reverses its time order. Writing P ~ = T − P 0 ​ ( P ) \\tilde{P}=T_{-P_{0}}(P) for the zeroed prime (so P ~ 0 = 0 \\tilde{P}_{0}=0 ), the four base forms, P P (prime), I I (inversion), R R (retrograde), and R ​ I RI (retrograde inversion), are b P = P ~ , b I = I ∘ P ~ , b R = rev ⁡ ( P ~ ) , b R ​ I = rev ⁡ ( I ∘ P ~ ) , b_{P}=\\tilde{P},\\;\\;b_{I}=I\\!\\circ\\!\\tilde{P},\\;\\;b_{R}=\\operatorname{rev}(\\tilde{P}),\\;\\;b_{RI}=\\operatorname{rev}(I\\!\\circ\\!\\tilde{P}), (4) and the row forms are their transpositions ℱ ​ ( P ) = { f X , n := T n ∘ b X : X ∈ { P , I , R , R ​ I } , n ∈ ℤ 12 } . \\mathcal{F}(P)=\\{f_{X,n}:=T_{n}\\circ b_{X}:X\\in\\{P,I,R,RI\\},\\ n\\in\\mathbb{Z}_{12}\\}. (5) These are the standard four row-form families (Babbitt 1960 ; Perle 1991 ) . Since ⟨ T n , I ⟩ \\langle T_{n},I\\rangle is the dihedral group D 12 D_{12} of order 24 24 and R R commutes with both pitch-class operations, retrograde contributes an independent factor of 2 2 . The transformation operations therefore form D 12 × C 2 D_{12}\\times C_{2} , of order 48 48 . Their action on a row produces at most 48 48 distinct row forms, because symmetries may cause forms to coincide; hence | ℱ ​ ( P ) | ≤ 48 \\lvert\\mathcal{F}(P)\\rvert\\leq 48 . Each f X , n = ( f X , n ​ [ 0 ] , … , f X , n ​ [ 11 ] ) f_{X,n}=(f_{X,n}[0],\\dots,f_{X,n}[11]) is itself an aggregate. Two structural properties of P P are used by setup-time constraints. Following the standard notion of derived rows (Babbitt 1960 ) , we call P P a derived row when its disjoint cells are related by standard serial transformations. For reproducible evaluation, our implementation operationalises this notion for cell sizes c ∈ { 3 , 4 , 6 } c\\in\\{3,4,6\\} ( c ∣ 12 c\\mid 12 ) by requiring every disjoint length- c c block in the partition of P P to share the canonical normalisation obtained by taking the minimum over {forward, retrograde, inverted, inverted-retrograde}. Two forms f , g f,g are hexachordally combinatorial if their first hexachords partition the aggregate: { f ​ [ 0..5 ] } ∩ { g ​ [ 0..5 ] } = ∅ \\{f[0..5]\\}\\cap\\{g[0..5]\\}=\\varnothing and { f ​ [ 0..5 ] } ∪ { g ​ [ 0..5 ] } = ℤ 12 \\{f[0..5]\\}\\cup\\{g[0..5]\\}=\\mathbb{Z}_{12} (Babbitt 1960 ) . 3.3 Compositions, Traces, and Core Event Consistency An event is a tuple e = ( τ , δ , m → , v , ϕ , σ ) e=(\\tau,\\delta,\\vec{m},v,\\phi,\\sigma) with onset τ ∈ ℚ ≥ 0 \\tau\\in\\mathbb{Q}_{\\geq 0} , duration δ > 0 \\delta>0 , MIDI pitches m → ∈ ℤ k \\vec{m}\\in\\mathbb{Z}^{k} ( k ≥ 1 k\\geq 1 ; k > 1 k>1 is a chord), a voice label v v , a row-form tag ϕ ∈ ℱ ​ ( P ) \\phi\\in\\mathcal{F}(P) , and an ordered tuple of row indices σ = ( s 1 , … , s r ) \\sigma=(s_{1},\\ldots,s_{r}) . Its pitch-class content is pc ⁡ ( e ) = { m mod 12 : m ∈ m → } \\operatorname{pc}(e)=\\{m\\bmod 12:m\\in\\vec{m}\\} and its sounding interval is ι ​ ( e ) = [ τ , τ + δ ) \\iota(e)=[\\tau,\\tau+\\delta) . A composition is a finite multiset of events S = { e 1 , … , e N } S=\\{e_{1},\\dots,e_{N}\\} ; its restriction to voice v v , written S v S_{v} , is the event stream of that voice ordered by onset. For a retained candidate, 𝐩 ~ 𝒯 ​ ( e ) \\widetilde{\\mathbf{p}}_{\\mathcal{T}}(e) denotes the ordered pitch-class tuple stored separately in the trace; unlike pc ⁡ ( e ) \\operatorname{pc}(e) , it is not defined by reducing m → \\vec{m} modulo 12 12 . Hard constraints. For fixed prime row P P and blueprint B B , each hard rule is a predicate H P , B : S ↦ { ⊤ , ⊥ } H_{P,B}:\\,S\\mapsto\\{\\top,\\bot\\} . The formal target set ℋ \\mathcal{H} is summarised in Table 5 (Appendix B ); the online harness records attempted enforcement, while the final release audit evaluates a broader subset directly on retained artefacts. The principal target predicates are: • Tagged row consistency ( H row H_{\\mathrm{row}} ): each retained event satisfies pc ⁡ ( e ) = { f ϕ ​ [ s ] : s ∈ σ } \\operatorname{pc}(e)=\\{f_{\\phi}[s]:s\\in\\sigma\\} for its tagged ( ϕ , σ ) (\\phi,\\sigma) , and the ordered tags are monotone in the scheduled row-form stream. Because an unrepaired proposal may be dropped while its cursor advances, the retained line can be a tag-preserving subsequence of that stream; it need not be a complete concatenation of forms. • Aggregate / no premature repetition ( H agg H_{\\mathrm{agg}} ): within every uninterrupted retained row cycle, no pitch class recurs before the cycle advances, except when the online state admits a local (oscillation/tremolo) window. In the implementation this window is inferred from recent cursor history rather than pre-authorised by a separate blueprint field. Aggregate completion is reported separately because dropped events can leave a cycle incomplete. • Vertical non-collision ( H ⟂ H_{\\perp} ): for events e , e ′ e,e^{\\prime} in distinct voices with overlapping sounding intervals ( | ι ​ ( e ) ∩ ι ​ ( e ′ ) | > ϵ \\lvert\\iota(e)\\cap\\iota(e^{\\prime})\\rvert>\\epsilon ), pc ⁡ ( e ) ∩ pc ⁡ ( e ′ ) = ∅ \\operatorname{pc}(e)\\cap\\operatorname{pc}(e^{\\prime})=\\varnothing ; the positive tolerance ϵ \\epsilon guards against floating-point boundary contact. The process verifier uses ϵ = 10 − 6 \\epsilon=10^{-6} beats; the independent comparison checker uses the more conservative 10 − 3 10^{-3} -beat threshold reported with that metric. • Octave equivalence ( H 8 H_{8} ): the independently stored trace tuple agrees with the retained MIDI pitches, H 8 ​ ( e , 𝒯 ) \\displaystyle H_{8}(e,\\mathcal{T}) ⇔ 𝐩 ~ 𝒯 ​ ( e ) \\displaystyle\\iff\\widetilde{\\mathbf{p}}_{\\mathcal{T}}(e) = ( m 1 mod 12 , … , m k mod 12 ) . \\displaystyle=(m_{1}\\bmod 2,\\ldots,m_{k}\\bmod 2). • No global rest / voice independence ( H tex H_{\\mathrm{tex}} ): in sections with at least two active voices, at every time in the active span at least one voice sounds; and the fraction of noteheads participating in any simultaneous higher/lower-voice register inversion is at most 0.1 0.1 . Setup-time predicates ( H seg H_{\\mathrm{seg}} , H der H_{\\mathrm{der}} , H comb H_{\\mathrm{comb}} ) check segmentation length consistency, derived-row identity, and hexachordal combinatoriality against P P and the blueprint. Definition 1 (Core event-consistency language) The core event-consistency language for P P and B B is ℒ ​ ( P , B ) = { S : ∀ H P , B ∈ ℋ , H P , B ​ ( S ) = ⊤ } \\mathcal{L}(P,B)=\\{S:\\forall H_{P,B}\\in\\mathcal{H},\\ H_{P,B}(S)=\\top\\} . This target language does not by itself require nonempty output, realisation of every requested voice, or completion of every aggregate; those coverage properties are reported separately. We therefore do not use membership in ℒ ​ ( P , B ) \\mathcal{L}(P,B) as a synonym for complete twelve-tone legality. Algorithm 1 Generate–verify–repair candidate construction for one section: release occurs only after the full-score audit. Input : section spec, voice states { u v } \\{u_{v}\\} , row engine on P P Parameter : max attempts K K ( K = 3 K=3 with replan; K = 1 K=1 without) Output : retained candidate events (release follows full-score audit) 1: S ⋆ ← ∅ S^{\\star}\\leftarrow\\varnothing ; m ⋆ ← ∞ m^{\\star}\\leftarrow\\infty 2: { u v 0 } ← Snapshot ​ ( { u v } ) \\{u_{v}^{0}\\}\\leftarrow\\textsc{Snapshot}(\\{u_{v}\\}) 3: for att = 1 \\mathrm{att}=1 to K K do 4: { u v } ← Clone ​ ( { u v 0 } ) \\{u_{v}\\}\\leftarrow\\textsc{Clone}(\\{u_{v}^{0}\\}) {no cursor state leaks across attempts} 5: propose candidate events per voice (LLM or deterministic), concurrently 6: sort candidates by ( τ , v ) (\\tau,v) ; assign event ids {determinism} 7: for each candidate e e in order do 8: e ′ ← ρ ⋆ ​ ( e ∣ accepted , u v ) e^{\\prime}\\leftarrow\\rho^{\\star}(e\\mid\\text{accepted},u_{v}) {bounded escalation} 9: if e ′ ≠ ⊥ e^{\\prime}\\neq\\bot then 10: accept e ′ e^{\\prime} 11: end if 12: Advance ​ ( u v ) \\textsc{Advance}(u_{v}) {cursor advances even if dropped} 13: end for 14: evaluate section-level and multi-voice hard rules; let S att S_{\\mathrm{att}} be the result 15: if | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S att ) | < m ⋆ \\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S_{\\mathrm{att}})\\rvert<m^{\\star} then 16: S ⋆ ← S att S^{\\star}\\leftarrow S_{\\mathrm{att}} ; m ⋆ ← | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S att ) | m^{\\star}\\leftarrow\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S_{\\mathrm{att}})\\rvert 17: end if 18: if m ⋆ = 0 m^{\\star}=0 then 19: break 20: end if 21: Replan : reassign row forms to minimise simulated collisions (guarded) 22: end for 23: return candidate S ⋆ S^{\\star} The implementation reconstructs the per-voice states from the events accepted before this section at the start of every attempt. Cursor advances made by a failed attempt therefore do not affect later attempts; only the operative section specification may change through replanning. The algorithmic replan may alter the operative section and row-form schedule within an attempt. The retained result currently stores the initial blueprint rather than a fully materialised history of those local replans. Consequently, agreement with the stored schedule is reported separately as a provenance check and is not implied by a process pass. An ideal final-score verifier 𝒱 \\mathcal{V} maps a composition to the multiset of hard violations, 𝒱 ​ ( S ) = { ( H , w ) : H ∈ ℋ , w ​ witnesses ​ ¬ H ​ ( S ) } \\mathcal{V}(S)=\\{(H,w):H\\in\\mathcal{H},\\ w\\text{ witnesses }\\neg H(S)\\} , so S ∈ ℒ ​ ( P , B ) ⇔ 𝒱 ​ ( S ) = ∅ S\\in\\mathcal{L}(P,B)\\iff\\mathcal{V}(S)=\\varnothing . Soft (aesthetic) rules are collected separately as warnings and never affect membership in ℒ \\mathcal{L} . The implemented process diagnostic instead reads violations accumulated during online generation; write this list as 𝒱 ^ proc \\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}} . It is not a fresh evaluation of every predicate on the final normalised candidate. Traces. Every accepted event e e carries a certificate c 𝒯 ​ ( e ) = ( τ , δ , m → , 𝐩 ~ 𝒯 , v , q , ϕ , σ , status , owner ) c_{\\mathcal{T}}(e)=(\\tau,\\delta,\\vec{m},\\widetilde{\\mathbf{p}}_{\\mathcal{T}},v,q,\\phi,\\sigma,\\text{status},\\text{owner}) , where q q is the section identifier. Thus MIDI pitches and claimed pitch classes are separately serialised rather than identified by definition. The implementation additionally stores event ids, repair history, and acceptance flags. The trace 𝒯 ​ ( S ) = { c 𝒯 ​ ( e ) : e ∈ S } \\mathcal{T}(S)=\\{c_{\\mathcal{T}}(e):e\\in S\\} is a per-event provenance log; it is used by higher process-acceptance tiers (Section 3.5 ) to test whether a claimed pitch class is derivable from a recorded row position. It is an auditable implementation record, not an independent certificate of the entire retained candidate. 3.4 The Generate–Verify–Repair Harness The harness maps a natural-language brief x x to either a verified composition or an explicit failure status. It first constructs a candidate S ⋆ S^{\\star} , with the design goal of reducing | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ⋆ ) | \\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{\\star})\\rvert to zero within a bounded attempt budget. A theme compiler turns x x into a structured specification θ ​ ( x ) \\theta(x) (bar counts, voice counts, textures, derived / combinatorial requests, etc.), which a planner expands into a blueprint of sections; the prime row P P is generated deterministically from the compiled specification once per task and is then held fixed across models, conditions, and the three runs. Within each section the harness runs Algorithm 1 ; after assembly, the final audit of Section 3.5 gates release. Composer-facing control. The harness also accepts hand-authored blueprints through the same verify–repair procedure. Composers can specify P P , up to four voices, and per-voice row forms and schedules, register [ ℓ v , h v ] [\\ell_{v},h_{v}] , rhythmic density, trichordal/tetrachordal/hexachordal segmentation, optional hexachordal combinatoriality, and staggered entries. These are executable inputs: repair enforces registers, although local replanning may revise schedules. This supports direct control over an individual serial practice, but is not evaluated; the benchmark uses only blueprints automatically synthesised from briefs. Row-preserving repair. The repair operator is an ordered escalation ladder ρ = ( ρ 1 , … , ρ 5 ) \\rho=(\\rho_{1},\\dots,\\rho_{5}) applied to a flagged event; ρ ⋆ ​ ( e ) \\rho^{\\star}(e) returns the first ρ j ​ ( e ) \\rho_{j}(e) that clears the local violation, or ⊥ \\bot (drop the event and defer its slot to a section replan) if none do. The first three rungs target vertical collisions by editing only timing : ρ j ​ ( e ) = ( τ ′ , δ ′ , m → , v , ϕ , σ ) , j ∈ { 1 , 2 , 3 } , \\rho_{j}(e)=(\\tau^{\\prime},\\delta^{\\prime},\\vec{m},v,\\phi,\\sigma),\\quad j\\in\\{1,2,3\\}, (6) i.e. ρ 1 ​ – ​ 3 \\rho_{1\\text{--}3} change ( τ , δ ) (\\tau,\\delta) but leave ( m → , ϕ , σ ) (\\vec{m},\\phi,\\sigma) fixed: rung 1 trims the current note’s tail, rung 2 yields by trimming an overlapping sustained note in another voice, rung 3 retimes the note inside its own free window. The last two rungs are LLM patches checked again after register clamping (rung 4 edits the single event and rung 5 rewrites its row segment), after which the event is dropped and the section is flagged for replan. The following invariance applies only to the deterministic timing rungs: Lemma 1 (Repair invariance) For j ∈ { 1 , 2 , 3 } j\\in\\{1,2,3\\} , pc ⁡ ( ρ j ​ ( e ) ) = pc ⁡ ( e ) \\operatorname{pc}(\\rho_{j}(e))=\\operatorname{pc}(e) and the tagged ( ϕ , σ ) (\\phi,\\sigma) are unchanged. Hence the deterministic rungs preserve H row H_{\\mathrm{row}} and H agg H_{\\mathrm{agg}} and do not alter MIDI pitch content. H 8 H_{8} is evaluated after the repaired event is serialised into the trace. Since the rungs only shorten or move into free space , they introduce no new vertical collision or intra-voice overlap. Rung 2 additionally shortens the overlapping sustained note in the other voice; being again only a truncation, it creates no new collision and leaves that voice’s pitch classes and row tags intact, so the invariance extends to every event the rung edits. Lockstep invariant. Generation and verification maintain a shared row cursor per voice. Even when ρ ⋆ ​ ( e ) = ⊥ \\rho^{\\star}(e)=\\bot , the Advance step of Algorithm 1 still increments the cursor, so the verifier’s expected row index never lags the generator’s. Proposition 1 (Cursor lockstep) At every step, for each voice v v the verifier-side next index equals the generator-side next index. Consequently a dropped event costs exactly one rest at its slot and does not desynchronise later tags. More generally, a dropped multi-index candidate omits its tagged row slice. The retained stream is therefore a tag-preserving subsequence, not necessarily a complete row statement. Bounded best-attempt selection. Let S ( 1 ) , … , S ( K ) S^{(1)},\\dots,S^{(K)} be the per-attempt results and S ⋆ = arg ⁡ min k ⁡ | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ( k ) ) | S^{\\star}=\\arg\\min_{k}\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{(k)})\\rvert the retained candidate (“take-best”). Proposition 2 (Projection and selection) (i) Within a fixed attempt and relative to its operative local section state, candidate construction, tag checking, and the deterministic repair rungs preserve each retained event’s expected row pitch class and octave-equivalent tag; later events remain aligned after a drop by Proposition 1 . This is an event-local invariant and does not imply that every requested aggregate is complete or that the event schedule matches the initial blueprint retained in the artefact. (ii) If M K = min 1 ≤ k ≤ K ⁡ | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ( k ) ) | M_{K}=\\min_{1\\leq k\\leq K}\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{(k)})\\rvert , then M K + 1 ≤ M K , | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ⋆ ) | = M K , M_{K+1}\\leq M_{K},\\qquad\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{\\star})\\rvert=M_{K}, so retaining an additional attempt cannot worsen the best observed violation count. (iii) No existence claim follows from the bounded search: the retained candidate can contain violations and therefore fail the final release gate. 3.5 Process Diagnostics and Final Release Audit For harness runs, we retain a chain of increasingly strict process acceptance predicates over a composition S S for brief x x , supporting transparent stage-wise diagnostic reporting: A leg ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\mathrm{leg}}(S) = [ 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ) = ∅ ] , \\displaystyle=\\bigl[\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S)=\\varnothing\\bigr], (7) A tr ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\mathrm{tr}}(S) = A leg ​ ( S ) ∧ [ | 𝒯 ​ ( S ) | = | S | ] , \\displaystyle=A_{\\mathrm{leg}}(S)\\wedge\\bigl[\\lvert\\mathcal{T}(S)\\rvert=\\lvert S\\rvert\\bigr], (8) A θ ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\theta}(S) = A tr ​ ( S ) ∧ Θ ​ ( S , θ ​ ( x ) ) , \\displaystyle=A_{\\mathrm{tr}}(S)\\wedge\\Theta\\bigl(S,\\theta(x)\\bigr), (9) A dist ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\mathrm{dist}}(S) = A θ ​ ( S ) ∧ C dist ​ ( S ) , \\displaystyle=A_{\\theta}(S)\\wedge C_{\\mathrm{dist}}(S), (10) Here Θ \\Theta checks bar/voice counts and requested techniques, while C dist C_{\\mathrm{dist}} requires attacks in at least 75 % 75\\% of each active voice’s bars. The diagnostics are nested: A dist ⇒ A θ ⇒ A tr ⇒ A leg . A_{\\mathrm{dist}}\\Rightarrow A_{\\theta}\\Rightarrow A_{\\mathrm{tr}}\\Rightarrow A_{\\mathrm{leg}}. (11) These tiers reuse process records and are diagnostics, not release decisions. After score assembly, the separately implemented constraint audit A audit A_{\\mathrm{audit}} (Appendix B ) rescans the retained candidate. The output contract is Compose ​ ( x ) = { S ⋆ , A audit ​ ( S ⋆ ) = 1 , Failure , otherwise . \\textsc{Compose}(x)=\\begin{cases}S^{\\star},&A_{\\mathrm{audit}}(S^{\\star})=1,\\\\ \\textsc{Failure},&\\text{otherwise}.\\end{cases} The gate does not trigger further generation; failed candidates remain stored only for analysis. Stored-blueprint agreement is reported separately because operative replans are not fully materialised. Figure 2: Per-model cross-voice collision rates for raw and harness candidates, normalised by overlapping cross-voice event pairs (overlap > 10 − 3 >10^{-3} beats). Dashed hollow lines denote raw candidates and solid filled lines denote harness candidates. Points show three-run means after pooling retained overlap pairs within each setting; error bars show one standard deviation. Raw rates are conditional on parseability. One-voice rates are zero by convention because no cross-voice pair exists. 4 Experimental Design Tasks. We use 40 40 single-factor tasks: a 20 20 -task length sweep ( 8 8 – 64 64 bars, two voices) and a 20 20 -task texture sweep ( 1 1 – 4 4 voices, eight bars), sharing a two-voice/eight-bar anchor. Each task contains one mild writing concern. Full briefs and inventories appear in Appendix C . Models. DeepSeek V4 Pro/Flash, GPT-5 Nano, and Qwen3 235B-A22B (Qwen3 235B) run both raw and in-harness. The full model inventory appears in Appendix C . Expert evaluation. Five experts compare 24 24 anonymised Qwen3 235B pairs ( 8 8 tasks × \\times three contrasts). Experimental setup. The four paired models share one API and decoding configuration (Appendix D ). A task’s prime row is fixed across models, conditions, and runs; seeds control only LLM sampling. After averaging runs within task, we report point estimates and 2000 2000 -resample nonparametric family-clustered bootstrap (Efron 1979 ) confidence intervals (CIs). Each draw samples the ten prompt families with their four tasks. The ablation study comprises the deterministic backbone, raw generation, Self-Refine, Soft rules, and the full harness. Metrics. We report process diagnostics, constraint-wise marginal pass rates, audited delivery yield, and a narrower, separately implemented collision and serialisation-consistency check. Other outcomes are corpus squared maximum mean discrepancy (MMD 2 ) (Gretton et al. 2012 ) with a Gaussian radial basis function (RBF) kernel and Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence (Kullback and Leibler 1951 ) (Appendix A ), degeneracy (Appendix B ), cost (Appendix H ), and expert preference (Appendix I ). Red-team analysis combines degeneracy, retained material, and the independent check rather than relying on process fields. 5 Results and Analysis 5.1 Length and Texture Scaling Harness collision rates remain at or below 2.05 % 2.05\\% across plotted settings, whereas parseable raw candidates reach 14.76 % 14.76\\% and show no common length trend (Figure 2 ). Full rates and denominator caveats appear in Appendix B . Audited delivery yield rises from 64 / 480 64/480 raw candidates ( 13.3 % 13.3\\% ) to 231 / 480 231/480 harness candidates ( 48.1 % 48.1\\% ); the harness explicitly fails rather than releasing the remaining 249 249 . The narrower collision and serialisation-consistency check rises from 33.5 % 33.5\\% to 58.3 % 58.3\\% (Table 17 ). Across the same four models, raw generation produces parseable candidates in 410 / 480 410/480 runs ( 85.4 % 85.4\\% ), whereas the harness does so in 480 / 480 480/480 (Table 12 ). Red-team parseability appears in Appendix F . Constraint-wise diagnosis. Marginal rates show that the harness passes row-form/order ( 99.4 % 99.4\\% ), no premature repetition ( 99.8 % 99.8\\% ), aggregate completion ( 95.6 % 95.6\\% ), and the voice-crossing bound ( 96.0 % 96.0\\% ) in nearly all candidates. The remaining bottlenecks are vertical non-collision ( 58.3 % 58.3\\% ) and the combined texture check ( 74.6 % 74.6\\% ). Vertical non-collision determines the equal-valued narrow collision and serialisation-consistency conjunction because its other components pass for every harness candidate. Thus, the 48.1 % 48.1\\% delivery yield is a conjunction across heterogeneous checks, not typical per-constraint performance (Appendix B , Table 6 ). Table 1 shows that repair raises process acceptance but not the narrow candidate check. Without repair, candidates contain 11.2 11.2 fewer events ( 0.71 0.71 fewer notes/bar) on average, consistent with reduced collision exposure; coverage changes by only − 0.001 -0.001 . Thus the + 0.050 +0.050 narrow-check delta is not evidence against local repair efficacy. More details appear in Appendix G . Table 1: Ablation and prompt-only deltas versus matching full-harness baselines. The top block is deterministic; lower blocks use Qwen3 235B. Values cover 40 40 paired tasks; “accept” is a process outcome, not an independent legality measure. Condition Δ \\Delta process accept Δ \\Delta ind. core Δ \\Delta deg. Deterministic backbone (vs. full harness) No repair − - 0.192 + + 0.050 − - 0.006 No repair + no replan − - 0.192 + + 0.025 − - 0.004 No replan − - 0.025 + + 0.025 + + 0.001 LLM in the loop (vs. full harness) No skills + + 0.017 − - 0.042 + + 0.000 Fixed row − - 0.008 − - 0.092 + + 0.001 Prompt-only baselines (vs. full harness) Self-refine − - 0.183 − - 0.333 + + 0.241 Soft rules − - 0.237 − - 0.400 + + 0.208 Figure 3: Per-model raw vs. harness candidate comparison. Panels report the independent collision and serialisation-consistency pass rate, degeneracy score, and parseable-candidate rate. Bars show one standard deviation. Unparseable raw candidates fail the independent check; raw degeneracy is conditional on parseability. 5.2 Robustness to Degeneracy-Inducing Prompts Tables 10 and 11 (Appendix F ) report the exploratory end-to-end prompt stress test on Qwen3 235B. Because attack suffixes also pass through the theme compiler, they can change the executable specification rather than attacking a fixed proposer alone. Harness degeneracy stays near 0.05 0.05 and its collision and serialisation-consistency pass rate remains at 0.55 0.55 – 0.65 0.65 , but the Long chords variant eliminates theme coverage. 5.3 Capability–Scaffolding Interaction and Cost For each harness-tier model, in-harness vs. raw generation (Table 17 , Appendix H ) raises the independent collision and serialisation-consistency pass rate from 0.27 0.27 – 0.46 0.46 to 0.53 0.53 – 0.63 0.63 , raises audited delivery yield from 0.06 0.06 – 0.23 0.23 to 0.43 0.43 – 0.52 0.52 , and cuts degeneracy from 0.13 0.13 – 0.24 0.24 to 0.047 0.047 – 0.053 0.053 . This descriptively supports a scaffolding effect for the four tested models, not a general democratisation claim. Table 2 reports the associated test-time cost. The full harness averages 638 638 calls, 823 823 k tokens, and 841 841 seconds per run, versus one call, 5.3 5.3 k tokens, and 77 77 seconds for raw generation. Across conditions, these gains coincide with 638 638 times as many calls, 157 157 times as many tokens, and 11 11 times the latency on the evaluated Qwen3 235B runs. Table 2: Mean per-run cost on Qwen3 235B ( n ≈ 110 ​ – ​ 120 n\\approx 110\\text{--}120 ). Tokens are provider-reported total usage; wall-clock covers end-to-end execution. Condition LLM calls Tokens Wall-clock (s) Blueprint only 1.0 2,433 24.0 Raw LLM 1.0 5,257 76.7 Soft rules 1.0 5,117 62.8 Self-refine 5.0 23,850 223.9 Full harness, no skills 627.3 234,845 814.5 Full harness 638.0 823,482 841.0 5.4 Musical Quality Across matched tasks, harness candidates reduce mean degeneracy for every model, from 0.132 0.132 – 0.244 0.244 on parseable raw candidates to 0.047 0.047 – 0.053 0.053 (Figure 3 ; Table 17 ). A representative generated candidate is in Figure 4 in Appendix H . Corpus distribution analysis. Table 3 compares the retained harness candidates with a 20 20 -piece human corpus using pitch-distribution features (Appendix A ). Harness candidates are closer to the strict-serial than the free-atonal subset under both MMD 2 and KL. Task-completion analysis. Table 4 captures properties omitted by the corpus features. Every harness candidate is parseable, covers 97.3 % 97.3\\% of requested voice–bar cells, and completes aggregates in 95.6 % 95.6\\% of all runs; parseable raw candidates cover only 63.5 % 63.5\\% of voice–bar cells. Table 3: Corpus distribution distance for 480 480 retained harness candidates. One RBF bandwidth is shared. KL is interval-class / directed-interval / pitch-class, generated ∥ \\,\\|\\, corpus. Corpus subset n n MMD 2 KL (ic / di / pc) all 20 0.330 0.073 / 0.074 / 0.009 strict-serial 9 0.278 0.041 / 0.042 / 0.004 free-atonal 11 0.419 0.145 / 0.155 / 0.024 Table 4: Raw vs. harness candidate completion over 480 480 paired cells. Values are three-run mean ± \\pm standard deviation pooled over four models. Parseability and aggregate completion use the intention-to-treat denominator; coverage and voice realisation are conditional on parseable candidates. Metric Raw Harness Parseable-candidate rate 0.854 ± 0.055 0.854\\pm 0.055 1.000 ± 0.000 1.000\\pm 0.000 Active-bar coverage 0.635 ± 0.020 0.635\\pm 0.020 0.973 ± 0.001 0.973\\pm 0.001 Voice realisation 0.995 ± 0.005 0.995\\pm 0.005 1.000 ± 0.000 1.000\\pm 0.000 Aggregate-completion pass 0.673 ± 0.046 0.673\\pm 0.046 0.956 ± 0.006 0.956\\pm 0.006 5.5 Expert Blind Evaluation Five experts evaluate 24 24 anonymised retained-candidate pairs. The full harness receives 82 82 – 90 % 90\\% of choices over raw generation for adherence, perceived legality, coherence, and overall quality, and 70 % 70\\% for style. Against the ablations, full-harness win rates span 55 55 – 75 % 75\\% without skills and 57 57 – 75 % 75\\% without repair. Task-clustered intervals and low inter-rater agreement qualify these aggregate preferences (Appendix I ). 6 Conclusion and Limitations We cast twelve-tone composition as constrained generation and introduce a generate–verify–repair harness. The complete pipeline raises audited delivery yield, improves candidate consistency, and abstains on failed candidates, but costs far more than the baselines. Relaxed schedule provenance precludes whole-piece legality, while unmatched compute prevents attributing gains specifically to repair. Expert ratings cover five raters and eight tasks, while corpus distances use only twenty works and lack uncertainty estimates for subset comparisons. These constraints limit generalisation beyond the evaluated models and prompt families. Acknowledgements This work is supported by the Advanced Discipline Construction Project of Beijing Universities, the Special Programme of National Natural Science Foundation of China (Grant No. T2341003), and the Major Programme of National Social Science Fund of China (Grant No. 21ZD19). References K. Ahmed, K. Chang, and G. Van den Broeck (2023) A pseudo-semantic loss for autoregressive models with logical constraints . In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) , Cited by: §2 . D. Amodei, C. Olah, J. Steinhardt, P. Christiano, J. Schulman, and D. Mané (2016) Concrete problems in AI safety . External Links: 1606.06565 Cited by: §1 , §2 . M. Babbitt (1960) Twelve-tone invariants as compositional determinants . The Musical Quarterly 46 ( 2 ), pp. 246–259 . External Links: Document Cited by: §3.1 , §3.2 , §3.2 . A. Bonlarron and J. Régin (2024) Intertwining CP and NLP: the generation of unreasonably constrained sentences . In Proceedings of the International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence (IJCAI) , pp. 7600–7608 . External Links: Document Cited by: §2 . H. Dong, W. Hsiao, L. Yang, and Y. Yang (2018) MuseGAN: multi-track sequential generative adversarial networks for symbolic music generation and accompaniment . In Proceedings of the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence (AAAI) , Vol. 32 , pp. 34–41 . External Links: Document Cited by: §2 . B. Efron (1979) Bootstrap methods: another look at the jackknife . The Annals of Statistics 7 ( 1 ), pp. 1–26 . External Links: Document Cited by: §4 . M. Feitosa, R. S. Santos, and L. S. Cardoso (2022) An intervallic approach to tone r