stency language) The core event-consistency language for P P and B B is ℒ ​ ( P , B ) = { S : ∀ H P , B ∈ ℋ , H P , B ​ ( S ) = ⊤ } \\mathcal{L}(P,B)=\\{S:\\forall H_{P,B}\\in\\mathcal{H},\\ H_{P,B}(S)=\\top\\} . This target language does not by itself require nonempty output, realisation of every requested voice, or completion of every aggregate; those coverage properties are reported separately. We therefore do not use membership in ℒ ​ ( P , B ) \\mathcal{L}(P,B) as a synonym for complete twelve-tone legality. Algorithm 1 Generate–verify–repair candidate construction for one section: release occurs only after the full-score audit. Input : section spec, voice states { u v } \\{u_{v}\\} , row engine on P P Parameter : max attempts K K ( K = 3 K=3 with replan; K = 1 K=1 without) Output : retained candidate events (release follows full-score audit) 1: S ⋆ ← ∅ S^{\\star}\\leftarrow\\varnothing ; m ⋆ ← ∞ m^{\\star}\\leftarrow\\infty 2: { u v 0 } ← Snapshot ​ ( { u v } ) \\{u_{v}^{0}\\}\\leftarrow\\textsc{Snapshot}(\\{u_{v}\\}) 3: for att = 1 \\mathrm{att}=1 to K K do 4: { u v } ← Clone ​ ( { u v 0 } ) \\{u_{v}\\}\\leftarrow\\textsc{Clone}(\\{u_{v}^{0}\\}) {no cursor state leaks across attempts} 5: propose candidate events per voice (LLM or deterministic), concurrently 6: sort candidates by ( τ , v ) (\\tau,v) ; assign event ids {determinism} 7: for each candidate e e in order do 8: e ′ ← ρ ⋆ ​ ( e ∣ accepted , u v ) e^{\\prime}\\leftarrow\\rho^{\\star}(e\\mid\\text{accepted},u_{v}) {bounded escalation} 9: if e ′ ≠ ⊥ e^{\\prime}\\neq\\bot then 10: accept e ′ e^{\\prime} 11: end if 12: Advance ​ ( u v ) \\textsc{Advance}(u_{v}) {cursor advances even if dropped} 13: end for 14: evaluate section-level and multi-voice hard rules; let S att S_{\\mathrm{att}} be the result 15: if | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S att ) | < m ⋆ \\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S_{\\mathrm{att}})\\rvert<m^{\\star} then 16: S ⋆ ← S att S^{\\star}\\leftarrow S_{\\mathrm{att}} ; m ⋆ ← | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ (