er than identified by definition. The implementation additionally stores event ids, repair history, and acceptance flags. The trace 𝒯 ​ ( S ) = { c 𝒯 ​ ( e ) : e ∈ S } \\mathcal{T}(S)=\\{c_{\\mathcal{T}}(e):e\\in S\\} is a per-event provenance log; it is used by higher process-acceptance tiers (Section 3.5 ) to test whether a claimed pitch class is derivable from a recorded row position. It is an auditable implementation record, not an independent certificate of the entire retained candidate. 3.4 The Generate–Verify–Repair Harness The harness maps a natural-language brief x x to either a verified composition or an explicit failure status. It first constructs a candidate S ⋆ S^{\\star} , with the design goal of reducing | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ⋆ ) | \\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{\\star})\\rvert to zero within a bounded attempt budget. A theme compiler turns x x into a structured specification θ ​ ( x ) \\theta(x) (bar counts, voice counts, textures, derived / combinatorial requests, etc.), which a planner expands into a blueprint of sections; the prime row P P is generated deterministically from the compiled specification once per task and is then held fixed across models, conditions, and the three runs. Within each section the harness runs Algorithm 1 ; after assembly, the final audit of Section 3.5 gates release. Composer-facing control. The harness also accepts hand-authored blueprints through the same verify–repair procedure. Composers can specify P P , up to four voices, and per-voice row forms and schedules, register [ ℓ v , h v ] [\\ell_{v},h_{v}] , rhythmic density, trichordal/tetrachordal/hexachordal segmentation, optional hexachordal combinatoriality, and staggered entries. These are executable inputs: repair enforces registers, although local replanning may revise schedules. This supports direct control over an individual serial practice, but is not evaluated; the benchmark uses only blueprints automatically synthesised from briefs. Row-preserving repair. The repair operator is an ordered escalation ladder ρ = ( ρ 1 , … , ρ 5 ) \\rho=(\\rho_{1},\\dots,\\rho_{5}) applied to a flagged event; ρ ⋆ ​ ( e ) \\rho^{\\star}(e) returns the first ρ j ​ ( e ) \\rho_{j}(e) that clears the local violation, or ⊥ \\bot (drop the event and defer its slot to a section replan) if none do. The first three rungs target vertical collisions by editing only timing : ρ j ​ ( e ) = ( τ ′ , δ ′ , m → , v , ϕ , σ ) , j ∈ { 1 , 2 , 3 } , \\rho_{j}(e)=(\\tau^{\\prime},\\delta^{\\prime},\\vec{m},v,\\phi,\\sigma),\\quad j\\in\\{1,2,3\\}, (6) i.e. ρ 1 ​ – ​ 3 \\rho_{1\\text{--}3} change ( τ , δ ) (\\tau,\\delta) but leave ( m → , ϕ , σ ) (\\vec{m},\\phi,\\sigma) fixed: rung 1 trims the current note’s tail, rung 2 yields by trimming an overlapping sustained note in another voice, rung 3 retimes the note inside its own free window. The last two rungs are LLM patches checked again after register clamping (rung 4 edits the single event and rung 5 rewrites its row segment), after which the event is dropped and the section is flagged for replan. The following invariance applies only to the deterministic timing rungs: Lemma 1 (Repair invariance) For j ∈ { 1 , 2 , 3 } j\\in\\{1,2,3\\} , pc ⁡ ( ρ j ​ ( e ) ) = pc ⁡ ( e ) \\operatorname{pc}(\\rho_{j}(e))=\\operatorname{pc}(e) and the tagged ( ϕ , σ ) (\\phi,\\sigma) are unchanged. Hence the deterministic rungs preserve H row H_{\\mathrm{row}} and H agg H_{\\mathrm{agg}} and do not alter MIDI pitch content. H 8 H_{8} is evaluated after the repaired event is serialised into the trace. Since the rungs only shorten or move into free space , they introduce no new vertical collision or intra-voice overlap. Rung 2 additionally shortens the overlapping sustained note in the other voice; being again only a truncation, it creates no new collision and leaves that voice’s pitch classes and row tags intact, so the invariance extends to every event the rung edits. Lockstep invariant. Generation and verification maintain a shared row cursor per voice. Even when ρ ⋆ ​ ( e ) = ⊥ \\rho^{\\star}(e)=\\bot , the Advance step of Algorithm 1 still increments the cursor, so the verifier’s expected row index never lags the generator’s. Proposition 1 (Cursor lockstep) At every step, for each voice v v the verifier-side next index equals the generator-side next index. Consequently a dropped event costs exactly one rest at its slot and does not desynchronise later tags. More generally, a dropped multi-index candidate omits its tagged row slice. The retained stream is therefore a tag-preserving subsequence, not necessarily a complete row statement. Bounded best-attempt selection. Let S ( 1 ) , … , S ( K ) S^{(1)},\\dots,S^{(K)} be the per-attempt results and S ⋆ = arg ⁡ min k ⁡ | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ( k ) ) | S^{\\star}=\\arg\\min_{k}\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{(k)})\\rvert the retained candidate (“take-best”). Proposition 2 (Projection and selection) (i) Within a fixed attempt and relative to its operative local section state, candidate construction, tag checking, and the deterministic repair rungs preserve each retained event’s expected row pitch class and octave-equivalent tag; later events remain aligned after a drop by Proposition 1 . This is an event-local invariant and does not imply that every requested aggregate is complete or that the event schedule matches the initial blueprint retained in the artefact. (ii) If M K = min 1 ≤ k ≤ K ⁡ | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ( k ) ) | M_{K}=\\min_{1\\leq k\\leq K}\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{(k)})\\rvert , then M K + 1 ≤ M K , | 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ⋆ ) | = M K , M_{K+1}\\leq M_{K},\\qquad\\lvert\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S^{\\star})\\rvert=M_{K}, so retaining an additional attempt cannot worsen the best observed violation count. (iii) No existence claim follows from the bounded search: the retained candidate can contain violations and therefore fail the final release gate. 3.5 Process Diagnostics and Final Release Audit For harness runs, we retain a chain of increasingly strict process acceptance predicates over a composition S S for brief x x , supporting transparent stage-wise diagnostic reporting: A leg ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\mathrm{leg}}(S) = [ 𝒱 ^ proc ​ ( S ) = ∅ ] , \\displaystyle=\\bigl[\\widehat{\\mathcal{V}}_{\\mathrm{proc}}(S)=\\varnothing\\bigr], (7) A tr ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\mathrm{tr}}(S) = A leg ​ ( S ) ∧ [ | 𝒯 ​ ( S ) | = | S | ] , \\displaystyle=A_{\\mathrm{leg}}(S)\\wedge\\bigl[\\lvert\\mathcal{T}(S)\\rvert=\\lvert S\\rvert\\bigr], (8) A θ ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\theta}(S) = A tr ​ ( S ) ∧ Θ ​ ( S , θ ​ ( x ) ) , \\displaystyle=A_{\\mathrm{tr}}(S)\\wedge\\Theta\\bigl(S,\\theta(x)\\bigr), (9) A dist ​ ( S ) \\displaystyle A_{\\mathrm{dist}}(S) = A θ ​ ( S ) ∧ C dist ​ ( S ) , \\displaystyle=A_{\\theta}(S)\\wedge C_{\\mathrm{dist}}(S), (10) Here Θ \\Theta checks bar/voice counts and requested techniques, while C dist C_{\\mathrm{dist}} requires attacks in at least 75 % 75\\% of each active voice’s bars. The diagnostics are nested: A dist ⇒ A θ ⇒ A tr ⇒ A leg . A_{\\mathrm{dist}}\\Rightarrow A_{\\theta}\\Rightarrow A_{\\mathrm{tr}}\\Rightarrow A_{\\mathrm{leg}}. (11) These tiers reuse process records and are diagnostics, not release decisions. After score assembly, the separately implemented constraint audit A audit A_{\\mathrm{audit}} (Appendix B ) rescans the retained candidate. The output contract is Compose ​ ( x ) = { S ⋆ , A audit ​ ( S ⋆ ) = 1 , Failure , otherwise . \\textsc{Compose}(x)=\\begin{cases}S^{\\star},&A_{\\mathrm{audit}}(S^{\\star})=1,\\\\ \\textsc{Failure},&\\text{otherwise}.\\end{cases} The gate does not trigger further generation; failed candidates remain stored only for analysis. Stored-blueprint agreement is reported separately because operative replans are not fully materialised. Figure 2: Per-model cross-voice collision rates for raw and harness candidates, normalised by overlapping cross-voice event pairs (overlap > 10 − 3 >10^{-3} beats). Dashed hollow lines denote raw candidates and solid filled lines denote harness candidates. Points show three-run means after pooling retained overlap pairs within each setting; error bars show one standard deviation. Raw rates are conditional on parseability. One-voice rates are zero by convention because no cross-voice pair exists. 4 Experimental Design Tasks. We use 40 40 single-factor tasks: a 20 20 -task length sweep ( 8 8 – 64 64 bars, two voices) and a 20 20 -task texture sweep ( 1 1 – 4 4 voices, eight bars), sharing a two-voice/eight-bar anchor. Each task contains one mild writing concern. Full briefs and inventories appear in Appendix C . Models. DeepSeek V4 Pro/Flash, GPT-5 Nano, and Qwen3 235B-A22B (Qwen3 235B) run both raw and in-harness. The full model inventory appears in Appendix C . Expert evaluation. Five experts compare 24 24 anonymised Qwen3 235B pairs ( 8 8 tasks × \\times three contrasts). Experimental setup. The four paired models share one API and decoding configuration (Appendix D ). A task’s prime row is fixed across models, conditions, and runs; seeds control only LLM sampling. After averaging runs within task, we report point estimates and 2000 2000 -resample nonparametric family-clustered bootstrap (Efron 1979 ) confidence intervals (CIs). Each draw samples the ten prompt families with their four tasks. The ablation study comprises the deterministic backbone, raw generation, Self-Refine, Soft rules, and the full harness. Metrics. We report process diagnostics, constraint-wise marginal pass rates, audited delivery yield, and a narrower, separately implemented collision and serialisation-consistency check. Other outcomes are corpus squared maximum mean discrepancy (MMD 2 ) (Gretton et al. 2012 ) with a Gaussian radial basis function (RBF) kernel and Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence (Kullback and Leibler 1951 ) (Appendix A ), degeneracy (Appendix B ), cost (Appendix H ), and expert preference (Appendix I ). Red-team analysis combines degeneracy, retained material, and the independent check rather than relying on process fields. 5 Results and Analysis 5.1 Length and Texture Scaling Harness collision rates remain at or below 2.05 % 2.05\\% across plotted settings, whereas parseable raw candidates reach 14.76 % 14.76\\% and show no common length trend (Figure 2 ). Full rates and denominator caveats appear in Appendix B . Audited delivery yield rises from 64 / 480 64/480 raw candidates ( 13.3 % 13.3\\% ) to 231 / 480 231/480 harness candidates ( 48.1 % 48.1\\% ); the harness explicitly fails rather than releasing the remaining 249 249 . The narrower collision and serialisation-consistency check rises from 33.5 % 33.5\\% to 58.3 % 58.3\\% (Table 17 ). Across the same four models, raw generation produces parseable candidates in 410 / 480 410/480 runs ( 85.4 % 85.4\\% ), whereas the harness does so in 480 / 480 480/480 (Table 12 ). Red-team parseability appears in Appendix F . Constraint-wise diagnosis. Marginal rates show that the harness passes row-form/order ( 99.4 % 99.4\\% ), no premature repetition ( 99.8 % 99.8\\% ), aggregate completion ( 95.6 % 95.6\\% ), and the voice-crossing bound ( 96.0 % 96.0\\% ) in nearly all candidates. The remaining bottlenecks are vertical non-collision ( 58.3 % 58.3\\% ) and the combined texture check ( 74.6 % 74.6\\% ). Vertical non-collision determines the equal-valued narrow collision and serialisation-consistency conjunction because its other components pass for every harness candidate. Thus, the 48.1 % 48.1\\% delivery yield is a conjunction across heterogeneous checks, not typical per-constraint performance (Appendix B , Table 6 ). Table 1 shows that repair raises process acceptance but not the narrow candidate check. Without repair, candidates contain 11.2 11.2 fewer events ( 0.71 0.71 fewer notes/bar) on average, consistent with reduced collision exposure; coverage changes by only − 0.001 -0.001 . Thus the + 0.050 +0.050 narrow-check delta is not evidence against local repair efficacy. More details appear in Appendix G . Table 1: Ablation and prompt-only deltas versus matching full-harness baselines. The top block is deterministic; lower blocks use Qwen3 235B. Values cover 40 40 paired tasks; “accept” is a process outcome, not an independent legality measure. Condition Δ \\Delta process accept Δ \\Delta ind. core Δ \\Delta deg. Deterministic backbone (vs. full harness) No repair − - 0.192 + + 0.050 − - 0.006 No repair + no replan − - 0.192 + + 0.025 − - 0.004 No replan − - 0.025 + + 0.025 + + 0.001 LLM in the loop (vs. full harness) No skills + + 0.017 − - 0.042 + + 0.000 Fixed row − - 0.008 − - 0.092 + + 0.001 Prompt-only baselines (vs. full harness) Self-refine − - 0.183 − - 0.333 + + 0.241 Soft rules − - 0.237 − - 0.400 + + 0.208 Figure 3: Per-model raw vs. harness candidate comparison. Panels report the independent collision and serialisation-consistency pass rate, degeneracy score, and parseable-candidate rate. Bars show one standard deviation. Unparseable raw candidates fail the independent check; raw degeneracy is conditional on parseability. 5.2 Robustness to Degeneracy-Inducing Prompts Tables 10 and 11 (Appendix F ) report the exploratory end-to-end prompt stress test on Qwen3 235B. Because attack suffixes also pass through the theme compiler, they can change the executable specification rather than attacking a fixed proposer alone. Harness degeneracy stays near 0.05 0.05 and its collision and serialisation-consistency pass rate remains at 0.55 0.55 – 0.65 0.65 , but the Long chords variant eliminates theme coverage. 5.3 Capability–Scaffolding Interaction and Cost For each harness-tier model, in-harness vs. raw generation (Table 17 , Appendix H ) raises the independent collision and serialisation-consistency pass rate from 0.27 0.27 – 0.46 0.46 to 0.53 0.53 – 0.63 0.63 , raises audited delivery yield from 0.06 0.06 – 0.23 0.23 to 0.43 0.43 – 0.52 0.52 , and cuts degeneracy from 0.13 0.13 – 0.24 0.24 to 0.047 0.047 – 0.053 0.053 . This descriptively supports a scaffolding effect for the four tested models, not a general democratisation claim. Table 2 reports the associated test-time cost. The full harness averages 638 638 calls, 823 823 k tokens, and 841 841 seconds per run, versus one call, 5.3 5.3 k tokens, and 77 77 seconds for raw generation. Across conditions, these gains coincide with 638 638 times as many calls, 157 157 times as many tokens, and 11 11 times the latency on the evaluated Qwen3 235B runs. Table 2: Mean per-run cost on Qwen3 235B ( n ≈ 110 ​ – ​ 120 n\\approx 110\\text{--}120 ). Tokens are provider-reported total usage; wall-clock covers end-to-end execution. Condition LLM calls Tokens Wall-clock (s) Blueprint only 1.0 2,433 24.0 Raw LLM 1.0 5,257 76.7 Soft rules 1.0 5,117 62.8 Self-refine 5.0 23,850 223.9 Full harness, no skills 627.3 234,845 814.5 Full harness 638.0 823,482 841.0 5.4 Musical Quality Across matched tasks, harness candidates reduce mean degeneracy for every model, from 0.132 0.132 – 0.244 0.244 on parseable raw candidates to 0.047 0.047 – 0.053 0.053 (Figure 3 ; Table 17 ). A representative generated candidate is in Figure 4 in Appendix H . Corpus distribution analysis. Table 3 compares the retained harness candidates with a 20 20 -piece human corpus using pitch-distribution features (Appendix A ). Harness candidates are closer to the strict-serial than the free-atonal subset under both MMD 2 and KL. Task-completion analysis. Table 4 captures properties omitted by the corpus features. Every harness candidate is parseable, covers 97.3 % 97.3\\% of requested voice–bar cells, and completes aggregates in 95.6 % 95.6\\% of all runs; parseable raw candidates cover only 63.5 % 63.5\\% of voice–bar cells. Table 3: Corpus distribution distance for 480 480 retained harness candidates. One RBF bandwidth is shared. KL is interval-class / directed-interval / pitch-class, generated ∥ \\,\\|\\, corpus. Corpus subset n n MMD 2 KL (ic / di / pc) all 20 0.330 0.073 / 0.074 / 0.009 strict-serial 9 0.278 0.041 / 0.042 / 0.004 free-atonal 11 0.419 0.145 / 0.155 / 0.024 Table 4: Raw vs. harness candidate completion over 480 480 paired cells. Values are three-run mean ± \\pm standard deviation pooled over four models. Parseability and aggregate completion use the intention-to-treat denominator; coverage and voice realisation are conditional on parseable candidates. Metric Raw Harness Parseable-candidate rate 0.854 ± 0.055 0.854\\pm 0.055 1.000 ± 0.000 1.000\\pm 0.000 Active-bar coverage 0.635 ± 0.020 0.635\\pm 0.020 0.973 ± 0.001 0.973\\pm 0.001 Voice realisation 0.995 ± 0.005 0.995\\pm 0.005 1.000 ± 0.000 1.000\\pm 0.000 Aggregate-completion pass 0.673 ± 0.046 0.673\\pm 0.046 0.956 ± 0.006 0.956\\pm 0.006 5.5 Expert Blind Evaluation Five experts evaluate 24 24 anonymised retained-candidate pairs. The full harness receives 82 82 – 90 % 90\\% of choices over raw generation for adherence, perceived legality, coherence, and overall quality, and 70 % 70\\% for style. Against the ablations, full-harness win rates span 55 55 – 75 % 75\\% without skills and 57 57 – 75 % 75\\% without repair. Task-clustered intervals and low inter-rater agreement qualify these aggregate preferences (Appendix I ). 6 Conclusion and Limitations We cast twelve-tone composition as constrained generation and introduce a generate–verify–repair harness. The complete pipeline raises audited delivery yield, improves candidate consistency, and abstains on failed candidates, but costs far more than the baselines. Relaxed schedule provenance precludes whole-piece legality, while unmatched compute prevents attributing gains specifically to repair. Expert ratings cover five raters and eight tasks, while corpus distances use only twenty works and lack uncertainty estimates for subset comparisons. These constraints limit generalisation beyond the evaluated models and prompt families. Acknowledgements This work is supported by the